    <p>
      Recall that <m>\cos(0)=0</m> but so do <m>\cos(0+2\pi)=\cos2\pi=0</m>.
      In fact, if we add or subtract any multiple of <m>2\pi</m> to our angle,
      we will obtain the same value for cosine.
      Functions such as these are known as
      <em>periodic functions</em>
    </p>
    <definition>
      <title>Periodic Function</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A function <m>f</m> is said to be <term>periodic</term>
              <idx><h>periodic</h></idx>
          if there exists a number <m>p>0</m> such that
          <me>
            f(\theta+p)=f(x)
          </me>
          for all <m>\theta</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>.
          The smallest value of the number <m>p</m> is called the <term>period</term>
              <idx><h>period</h></idx>
          of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def-periodic-properties">
    <title>Periodic Properties</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The six trigonometric functions are periodic functions.
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\sin\theta \amp  \cos(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\cos\theta \amp  \tan(\theta+\pi)\amp =\tan\theta</mrow>
            <mrow>\csc(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\csc\theta \amp  \sec(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\sec\theta \amp  \cot(\theta+\pi)\amp =\cot\theta</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="Trigonometry">Chapter</xref>, trigonometric functions use <m>\theta</m> or <m>t</m> for the variable in the domain of the function, 
      e.g. <m>y=\cos\theta</m>, <m>y=\sin t</m>.
      However, graphing functions on the <m>xy</m>-coordinate system traditionally use <m>x</m> for the variable in the domain.
      Therefore we will use the variable <m>x</m> when graphing trigonometric functions,  e.g. <m>y=\cos x</m>, <m>y=\sin x</m>.
    </p>
